ively, a variant of   Conyer  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Conyer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a minter, a coiner of money, from an agent derivative of Old French <i>coignier</i> ‘to stamp money, to mint’."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Roger de Conyers was born in 1156, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Roger de Conyers. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1156–":"1156–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1156":"1156","1150":"1150","Galfred, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1156–":"1156–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1156–Female":"1156–Kuollut","1190":"1190","about 1190":"noin 1190","1156":"1156","1150":"1150","Galfred, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1156–":"1156–Décédée","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1190–Male":"1190–Décédé","1156–Female":"